hints_latex:
Part (i) shows us that the order of \emph{a} modulo
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$ is equal to $\displaystyle 2^{\alpha}$.
Thus each of

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

are distinct odd numbers and thus each of the

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (-1)a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

are also distinct odd numbers. Hence it suffices to show that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (-1)a^{k} \not\equiv a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

for any $\displaystyle 0 \leq j,k \leq 2^{\alpha}-1$ and finish off the
proof with a counting argument.

sols_latex:
Repeating the hint, part (i) shows us that the order of \emph{a} modulo
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$ is equal to $\displaystyle 2^{\alpha}$.
Thus each of

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

are distinct odd numbers between 0 and $\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$ for
$\displaystyle 0 \leq j \leq 2^{\alpha}-1$ and thus each of the

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (-1)a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

are also distinct odd numbers between 0 and
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$. As there are $\displaystyle 2^{\alpha-1}$
total odd numbers between 0 and $\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$, we know
that provided all of the above numbers are distinct, we have found
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha} + 2^{\alpha} = 2^{\alpha+1}$ total odd numbers
and hence we can form a bijection. Hence it suffices to show that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (-1)a^{k} \not\equiv a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

for any $\displaystyle 0 \leq j,k \leq 2^{\alpha}-1$. This shows the
claim for all odd numbers since all odd numbers are equivalent modulo
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$ to an odd number between 0 and
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$.

Assume towards a contradiction that we found two such numbers:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (-1)a^{k} \equiv a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

Without loss of generality, suppose that $\displaystyle k \geq j$. Then,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle a^{k-j} \equiv -1 \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}

Once again, modulo 4 arguments (recalling that
$\displaystyle a \equiv 5 \mod{8}$) show that the left hand side above
is congruent to 1 modulo 4 and the right hand side is still congruent to
-1 modulo 4. This is a contradiction. Thus any odd number can be
expressed uniquely of the form

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle (-1)^{i}a^{j}
\end{align*}

with $\displaystyle i \in \{0,1\}$ and
$\displaystyle 0 \leq j \leq 2^{\alpha}-1$ as required.

statement_latex:
Let $\displaystyle a \in \mathbb{Z}$ such that
$\displaystyle a \equiv 5 \mod{8}$ and let
$\displaystyle \alpha \in \mathbb{N}$.

\textbf{(ii)} For each odd integer \emph{x}, prove that there exists a
unique $\displaystyle i \in \{0,1\}$ and a unique
$\displaystyle j \in \{0,1,2,...,2^{\alpha}-1\}$ such that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x \equiv (-1)^{i}a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}
\end{align*}
